The primary analysis has been done usin Nextflow-Core smRNASeq https://nf-co.re/smrnaseq

setwd("/storage2/Bermejo/miRNA/")

table2 <- read_csv("/storage2/Bermejo/miRNA/FASTQs/nextflow/edger/mature_counts.csv")
meta <- table2 %>% 
  dplyr::rename(sample = 1) %>% 
  dplyr::select(sample) %>% 
  mutate(condition = str_remove(sample,"\\d_1"))

cond <-  meta %>% 
  column_to_rownames("sample")

We use DESeq2 package for secondary analysis and Quality Control

We remove those transcripts with a total abundance lower than 10

table_sum <- table2 %>% rename(sample = 1) %>% column_to_rownames("sample") %>% t()



dds_gene <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData = table_sum %>% as.matrix(), 
                                   colData = cond, 
                                   design = ~condition)
## converting counts to integer mode
## Warning in DESeqDataSet(se, design = design, ignoreRank): some variables in
## design formula are characters, converting to factors
keep <- rowSums(counts(dds_gene)) >= 10
dds_gene <- dds_gene[keep,]
dds_gene <- DESeq(dds_gene)
## estimating size factors
## estimating dispersions
## gene-wise dispersion estimates
## mean-dispersion relationship
## final dispersion estimates
## fitting model and testing

Quality Control

To check the quality of the sample we test the homogenicity of the groups. In this case we represent the samples using Multi-Dimensional Scaling

mds <- counts(dds_gene, normalized = T) %>% 
  t() %>% vegdist(method = "euclidean") %>% 
  metaMDS()

mds$points %>% 
  as_tibble(rownames = "sample") %>% inner_join(meta) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = MDS1, y = MDS2, label = sample, color = condition))  + geom_point() + geom_text_repel() + scale_color_d3()
## Joining, by = "sample"

To test the homogenicity we perform a PERMANOVA test

dist <- counts(dds_gene, normalized = T) %>% 
  t() %>% vegdist(method = "euclidean")

adonis2(dist ~ condition, data = meta, permutations = 10000)
## Permutation test for adonis under reduced model
## Terms added sequentially (first to last)
## Permutation: free
## Number of permutations: 10000
## 
## adonis2(formula = dist ~ condition, data = meta, permutations = 10000)

## condition  5  82289852 0.31315 2.5532 0.0022 **

## Total     33 262777700 1.00000                 
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

The homogenicity of the groups is statistically significant so the sample quality is good enough

Statistical Test

All the test were performed at mature miRNA level. You can find all the table results at https://github.com/irycisBioinfo/miRnaSeqRosella

For each comparison we have performed an Gene Set Enrichment Analysis of GO term and KEGG pathways.

Control vs SIM

ctr_vs_sim_g <- results(dds_gene, contrast = c("condition","CTR","SIM"))

ctr_vs_sim_g %>% 
  as_tibble(rownames = "mirRNA") %>% 
  write_tsv("ctr_vs_sim.tsv")


ctr_vs_sim_g %>% 
  as_tibble(rownames = "mirRNA") %>%
  mutate(sig = ifelse(padj < 0.01,"Significative","No-Significative")) %>%
  mutate(label = ifelse(sig == "Significative",mirRNA,NA)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x= log2FoldChange, y = -log10(padj), color = sig, size = sqrt(baseMean), label = label)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_text_repel(size = 1)+
  scale_color_d3() +
  theme_light() + labs(title = "Control vs SIM")
## Warning: Removed 3 rows containing missing values (geom_point).
## Warning: Removed 643 rows containing missing values (geom_text_repel).
